31    /**
32    * This implementation delegates an method call to another method which can either be {@code static} by providing
33    * a reference to a {@link java.lang.Class} or an instance method when another object is provided. The potential
34    * targets of the method delegation can further be filtered by applying a filter. The method delegation can be
35    * customized by invoking the {@code MethodDelegation}'s several builder methods.
36    * <h3>Without any customization, the method delegation will work as follows:</h3>
37    * <span style="text-decoration: underline">Binding an instrumented method to a given delegate method</span>
38    * <p>&nbsp;</p>
39    * A method will be bound parameter by parameter. Considering a method {@code Foo#bar} being bound to a method
40    * {@code Qux#baz}, the method delegation will be decided on basis of the following annotations:
41    * <ul>
42    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Argument}:
43    * This annotation will bind the {@code n}-th parameter of {@code Foo#bar} to that parameter of {@code Qux#baz}that
44    * is annotated with this annotation where {@code n} is the obligatory argument of the {@code @Argument} annotation.</li>
45    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.AllArguments}:
46    * This annotation will assign a collection of all parameters of {@code Foo#bar} to that parameter of {@code Qux#baz}
47    * that is annotated with {@code AllArguments}.</li>
48    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.This}: A parameter
49    * of {@code Qux#baz} that is annotated with {@code This} will be assigned the instance that is instrumented for
50    * a non-static method.</li>
51    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Super}: A parameter that is annotated with
52    * this annotation is assigned a proxy that allows calling an instrumented type's super methods.</li>
53    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Default}: A parameter that is annotated with
54    * this annotation is assigned a proxy that allows calling an instrumented type's directly implemented interfaces'
55    * default methods.</li>
56    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.SuperCall}: A parameter
57    * of {@code Qux#baz} that is annotated with {@code SuperCall} will be assigned an instance of a type implementing both
58    * {@link java.lang.Runnable} and {@link java.util.concurrent.Callable} which will invoke the instrumented method on the
59    * invocation of either interface's method. The call is made using the original arguments of the method invocation.
60    * The return value is only emitted for the {@link java.util.concurrent.Callable#call()} method which additionally
61    * requires to catch any unchecked exceptions that might be thrown by the original method's implementation. If a
62    * source method is abstract, using this annotation excludes the method with this parameter annotation from being bound
63    * to this source method.
64    * </li>
65    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.DefaultCall}:
66    * This annotation is similar to the {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.SuperCall}
67    * annotation but it invokes a default method that is compatible to this method. If a source method does not represent
68    * a default method, using this annotation excludes the method with this parameter annotation from being bound to this
69    * source method.</li>
70    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Origin}: A parameter of
71    * {@code Qux#baz} that is annotated with {@code Origin} is assigned a reference to either a {@link java.lang.reflect.Method},
72    * a {@link java.lang.reflect.Constructor}, a {@code java.lang.reflect.Executable} or a {@link java.lang.Class} instance.
73    * A {@code Method}-typed, {@code Constructor} or {@code Executable} parameter is assigned a reference to the original
74    * method that is instrumented. A {@code Class}-typed parameter is assigned the type of the caller. Furthermore, {@code MethodType}
75    * and {@code MethodHandle} parameters are also supported. When using the annotation on a {@link java.lang.String} type,
76    * the intercepted method's {@code toString} value is injected. The same holds for a parameter of type {@code int} that receives
77    * the modifiers of the instrumented method.</li>
78    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.StubValue}: Assigns the (boxed) default value of the
79    * intercepted method's return type to the parameter. If the return type is {@code void}, {@code null} is assigned.</li>
80    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Empty}: Assigns the parameter type's
81    * default value, i.e. {@code null} for a reference type or zero for primitive types. This is an opportunity to
82    * ignore a parameter.</li>
83    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Pipe}: A parameter that is annotated
84    * with this annotation is assigned a proxy for forwarding the source method invocation to another instance of the
85    * same type as the declaring type of the intercepted method. <b>This annotation needs to be installed and explicitly
86    * registered before it can be used.</b> See the {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Pipe}
87    * annotation's documentation for further information on how this can be done.</li>
88    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Morph}: The morph annotation is similar to
89    * the {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.SuperCall} annotation but allows to
90    * explicitly define and therewith alter the arguments that are handed to the super method. <b>This annotation needs
91    * to be installed and explicitly registered before it can be used.</b> See the documentation to the annotation for
92    * further information.</li>
93    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.FieldValue}: Allows to access a field's value at the time
94    * of the method invocation. The field's value is directly assigned to the annotated parameter.</li>
95    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.FieldProxy}: Allows to access fields via getter
96    * and setter proxies. <b>This annotation needs to be installed and explicitly registered before it can be used.</b>
97    * Note that any field access requires boxing such that a use of {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.FieldAccessor} in
98    * combination with {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.MethodDelegation#andThen(Implementation)} might be a more
99    * performant alternative for implementing field getters and setters.</li>
100    * </ul>
101    * If a method is not annotated with any of the above methods, it will be treated as if it was annotated
102    * {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Argument} using the next
103    * unbound parameter index of the source method as its parameter. This means that a method
104    * {@code Qux#baz(@Argument(2) Object p1, Object p2, @Argument(0) Object p3} would be treated as if {@code p2} was annotated
105    * with {@code @Argument(1)}.
106    * <p>&nbsp;</p>
107    * In addition, the {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.RuntimeType}
108    * annotation can instruct a parameter to be bound by a
109    * {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bytecode.assign.Assigner} with considering the
110    * runtime type of the parameter.
111    * <p>&nbsp;</p>
112    * <span style="text-decoration: underline">Selecting among different methods that can be used for binding a method
113    * of the instrumented type</span>
114    * <p>&nbsp;</p>
115    * When deciding between two methods {@code Foo#bar} and {@code Foo#qux} that could both be used to delegating a
116    * method call, the following consideration is applied in the given order:
117    * <ol>
118    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.BindingPriority}:
119    * A method that is annotated with this annotation is given a specific priority where the default priority is set
120    * to {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.BindingPriority#DEFAULT}
121    * for non-annotated method. A method with a higher priority is considered a better target for delegation.</li>
122    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.DeclaringTypeResolver}:
123    * If a target method is declared by a more specific type than another method, the method with the most specific
124    * type is bound.</li>
125    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.MethodNameEqualityResolver}:
126    * If a source method {@code Baz#qux} is the source method, it will rather be assigned to {@code Foo#qux} because
127    * of their equal names. Similar names and case-insensitive equality are not considered.</li>
128    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.ArgumentTypeResolver}:
129    * The most specific type resolver will consider all bindings that are using the
130    * {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.Argument}
131    * annotation for resolving a binding conflict. In this context, the resolution will equal the most-specific
132    * type resolution that is performed by the Java compiler. This means that a source method {@code Bar#baz(String)}
133    * will rather be bound to a method {@code Foo#bar(String)} than {@code Foo#qux(Object)} because the {@code String}
134    * type is more specific than the {@code Object} type. If two methods are equally adequate by their parameter types,
135    * then the method with the higher numbers of {@code @Argument} annotated parameters is considered as the better
136    * delegation target.</li>
137    * <li>{@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.ParameterLengthResolver}:
138    * If a target methods has a higher number of total parameters that were successfully bound, the method with
139    * the higher number will be considered as the better delegation target.</li>
140    * </ol>
141    * <p>
142    * Additionally, if a method is annotated by
143    * {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.IgnoreForBinding},
144    * it is never considered as a target for a method delegation.
145    * </p>
146    * <p>
147    * <b>Important</b>: For invoking a method on another instance, use the {@link Forwarding} implementation. A method delegation
148    * intends to bind a interceptor class and its resolution algorithm will not necessarily yield a delegation to the intercepted
149    * method.
150    * </p>
151    *
152    * @see Forwarding
153    * @see net.bytebuddy.implementation.bind.annotation.TargetMethodAnnotationDrivenBinder.ParameterBinder.ForFixedValue
154    */

358    /**
359    * Creates an implementation where only instance methods of the given object are considered as binding targets.
360    * This method will never bind to constructors but will consider methods that are defined in super types. Note
361    * that this includes methods that were defined by the {@link java.lang.Object} class. You can narrow this default
362    * selection by explicitly selecting methods with calling the
363    * {@link net.bytebuddy.implementation.MethodDelegation#filter(net.bytebuddy.matcher.ElementMatcher)}
364    * method on the returned method delegation as for example:
365    * <pre>MethodDelegation.to(new Foo()).filter(MethodMatchers.not(isDeclaredBy(Object.class)));</pre>
366    * which will result in a delegation to <code>Foo</code> where no methods of {@link java.lang.Object} are considered
367    * for delegation.
368    *
369    * @param delegate A delegate instance which will be injected by a
